hypothesis testing

Load Packages

library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(infer)

Read in Sleep Data

sleep <- ggplot2::msleep %>% 
  clean_names()

Question 1.

Explore the dataset and familiarise yourself with it.

# dimensions of data 
dim(sleep)

# glimpse whole data set
glimpse(sleep)

Question 2.

Jabberwockies sleep for around 7 hours a night, on average. Perform an appropriate statistical test to determine whether the mean sleep_total in the sampled population of animal types differs from the typical value for jabberwockies.

Hypotheses

Null: There is no difference in mean sleep total and jabberwockies mean sleep.

\[H_0: \mu_{sleep\ total} = 7\]

Alternative: There is a statistically significant difference in mean sleep total and mean jabberwockies sleep.

\[H_A: \mu_{sleep\ total} \ne 7\] ### Alpha level

For the purposes of this hypothesis test, alpha = 0.05

Calculate observed statistic

obs_stat <- sleep %>% 
  summarise(mean_sleep_total = mean(sleep_total))

obs_stat

Create Null Sampling Distribution

null_dist <- sleep %>% 
  specify(response = sleep_total) %>% 
  hypothesise(null = "point", mu = 7) %>% 
  generate(reps = 10000, type = "bootstrap") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "mean")

null_dist
Response: sleep_total (numeric)
Null Hypothesis: point

Visualise Observed Stat on Null Sampling Distribution

null_dist %>% 
  visualise(bins = 30) +
  shade_p_value(obs_stat = obs_stat$mean_sleep_total, direction = "both")

Interpretation

Visually, it appears that there may be a statistically significant difference in the mean sleep total for the animals in our data set and the mean sleep for jabberwockies. This is due to the extreme right location of our observed statistic (red line) in relation to our normal sampling null distribution.

Calculate p-value

null_dist %>% 
  get_p_value(obs_stat = obs_stat, direction = "both")
Warning: Please be cautious in reporting a p-value of 0. This result is an approximation based on the number of `reps` chosen in the `generate()` step. See `?get_p_value()` for more information.

Outcome

Since our p-value of 0 < 0.05 (alpha), we reject the null hypothesis that the difference in mean sleep total and mean jabberwockie sleep is zero. It would appear that a more suitable assumption is that there is a statistically significant difference in the mean sleep totals of animals v jabberwockies.

Question 3.

Perform an appropriate statistical test to determine whether omnivores sleep for significantly longer than herbivores, on average.

Filter Sleep Data for Omnivores and Herbivores

omni_herbi_sleep <- sleep %>% 
  filter(vore %in% c("omni", "herbi"))

Hypotheses

H0: The mean sleep for omnivores <= mean sleep for herbivores

\[H_0: \mu_{omnivore\ sleep} =\ \mu_{herbivore\ sleep}\]

Ha: The mean sleep for omnivores > mean sleep for herbivores

\[H_A: \mu_{omnivore\ sleep} >\ \mu_{herbivore\ sleep}\]

Alpha Level

For this hypothesis test alpha = 0.05

Boxplot

omni_herbi_sleep %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = sleep_total, y = vore)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Calculate Observed Statistic


observed_stat <- omni_herbi_sleep %>% 
  specify(sleep_total~vore) %>% 
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c ("omni", "herbi"))
  
observed_stat
Response: sleep_total (numeric)
Explanatory: vore (factor)

Create Null Sampling Distribution

null_distribution <- omni_herbi_sleep %>% 
  specify(sleep_total~vore) %>% 
  hypothesise(null = "independence") %>% 
  generate(reps = 10000, type = "permute") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("omni", "herbi"))
  
null_distribution
Response: sleep_total (numeric)
Explanatory: vore (factor)
Null Hypothesis: independence

Visualise Null Sampling Distribution and Observed Statistic

null_distribution %>% 
  visualise(bins = 30) +
  shade_p_value(obs_stat = observed_stat, direction = "right")

H0: The mean sleep for omnivores = mean sleep for herbivores

\[H_0: \mu_{omnivore\ sleep} =\ \mu_{herbivore\ sleep}\]

Ha: The mean sleep for omnivores > mean sleep for herbivores

\[H_A: \mu_{omnivore\ sleep} >\ \mu_{herbivore\ sleep}\] ### Calculate p-value

null_distribution %>% 
  get_p_value(obs_stat = observed_stat, direction = "right")

Outcome

Since the p-value of 0.1232 > 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis and say that there is no statistically significant difference in mean sleep between omnivores and herbivores.
